# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: daniel-garrison-brinton
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The **Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University**, formerly the **Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia**, is the oldest natural science research institution and museum in the Americas.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was founded in 1812, by many of the leading naturalists of the young American republic with an expressed mission of "the encouragement and cultivation of the sciences".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It has sponsored expeditions, conducted original environmental and systematics research, and amassed natural history collections containing more than 17 million specimens.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy also organizes public exhibits and educational programs for both schools and the general public.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] During the first decades of the United States, Philadelphia was the cultural capital and one of the country's commercial centers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the city's institutions, the Library Company and the American Philosophical Society, were centers of enlightened thought and scientific inquiry.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The increasing sophistication of the earth and life sciences, combined with a growing awareness of the variety of life and landscape in the American wilderness, led a small group of naturalists to establish the Academy of Natural Sciences in the winter of 1812.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The academy was meant to foster a gathering of fellow naturalists and to nurture the growth and credibility of American science.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] They frequently looked to their European counterparts for inspiration and expertise and longed to be regarded as equals.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] On 25 April 1817 they were incorporated into the society under the title of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia by the legislature of Pennsylvania.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1 January 1818, eight members were published.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2011, the Academy became affiliated with nearby Drexel University and changed its name to the Academy of Natural Sciences of Drexel University.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Within a decade of its founding, the Academy became the undisputed center of natural sciences in the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy members were frequently enlisted to participate in national surveys of the western territories and other major expeditions.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Thomas Jefferson of Virginia, John Edwards Holbrook of South Carolina, Thomas Nuttall and Richard Owen of the United Kingdom, Georges Cuvier of France, and Alexander von Humboldt of Prussia were among the corresponding members (members who lived far from Philadelphia) of the Academy's first decades.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later during the 19th century, other notable naturalists and scientists, including John James Audubon, Charles S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, John Cassin, Edward Drinker Cope, Ezra Townsend Cresson, Richard Harlan, Ferdinand V.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, John Lawrence LeConte, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, George Ord, and James Rehn were members.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Corresponding members included Charles Darwin along with his supporters Asa Gray, and Thomas Henry Huxley.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] For much of its history, new members had to be nominated by two current members and then elected by the remaining members.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] These requirements were dropped in 1924.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable 20th-century scientists include James Böhlke, James Bond, Henry Weed Fowler, Ruth Patrick, Henry Pilsbry, H.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy of Natural Sciences holds an internationally important natural history collection.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, there are over 18 million biological specimens, and hundreds of thousands of volumes, journals, illustrations, photographs, and archival items in its library.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] These collections were obtained through multiple means, including the donation or purchase of existing collections or individual items, the collection activities of Academy-sponsored expeditions, or those of individual scientists, whether or not they work at the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some collections were originally gathered by other institutions.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a number of the natural history collections at the American Philosophical Society were relocated to the Academy by the end of the 19th century.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Traditionally, researchers at natural science (or natural history) institutions such as the Academy engaged in biological taxonomy, the science of discovering, describing, naming, and classifying species.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, research has shifted in emphasis to the science of systematics, the study of the evolutionary relationships among these species.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy preserves many type specimens, the reference material that helps establish a species' identity.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] They also preserve additional specimens with which scientists can investigate the nature of these species, their relationships with other species, their evolutionary history, or their conservation status.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's collections include a wide range of specimens across the tree of life.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also maintains several historically important collections.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Botany is study of plants, including nonvascular bryophytes (mosses, liverworts, and hornworts) and vascular plants, including ferns, conifers and flowering plants.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The field of botany has also traditionally included the study of algae, lichens, and fungi which are now classified in different biological kingdoms.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Collections at the Academy, which are housed in the Philadelphia Herbarium (PH), the oldest institutional herbarium in the New World, include some of the oldest and most important botanical collections in the Americas.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Notable early collectors include Benjamin Smith Barton, Constatine Rafinesque, Thomas Meehan, Thomas Nuttall, and Fredrick Pursh.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains approximately 1.5 million specimens of vascular plants, fungi, lichens, algae, and fossil plants, 40,000 of which are types.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also contains some special collections, including the plants collected by Johann and Georg Forster during the voyages of Captain James Cook, and by Meriwether Lewis during the Lewis and Clark expedition (Corps of Discovery).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department's current focus is plant biodiversity and evolution focusing on Apocynaceae (milkweed or dogbane family) and Polygalaceae.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's Diatom Herbarium, the largest in the Americas and the second largest in the world, contains approximately 220,000 slides of these microscopic algae.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herbarium contains many specimens contributed by notable collectors, a diversity of fossil diatoms, and diatoms collected as part of numerous freshwater environmental surveys in the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Diatom Herbarium also provides collections and taxonomic services for the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Former curators of note include Charles S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boyer, Ruth Patrick, and Charles Reimer.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Entomology has been important to the Academy since its founding.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of its earliest members include Thomas Say, regarded as the father of American entomology, and Titian Peale, a leading natural history illustrator and the chief naturalist on the United States Exploring Expedition (1834–1842).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The entomology collection currently contains more than 3.5 million specimens and includes the Titian Peale Moth and Butterfly Collection, the oldest entomology collection in the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, Daniel Otte, an expert on Orthoptera (crickets, grasshoppers, and their relatives) is a pioneer of presenting biological data on the internet through the creation of the Orthoptera Species File.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator and Entomology Department Chair, Jon Gelhaus is a leading expert on crane flies and manages the Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Ichthyology has also been a part of Academy collections and research since its beginnings, but the size of the collection was relatively modest until acquisition of Edward Drinker Cope's personal collections in 1898.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] A few years later, Henry Weed Fowler began his tenure at the Academy, during which he systematized the collections and described 1,408 species.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke, William Saul, and William Smith-Vaniz are among the scientists who followed Fowler.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Emeritus, John Lundberg, an expert in catfishes, pioneered deep channel collecting in large tropical rivers and is the lead author of a seminal scientific paper on the biological and geographic history of the Amazon River Basin.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ichthyology collection, which currently houses nearly 1.2 million specimens and nearly 3,000 types, is one of the most important such collections in the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The department also hosts the All Catfish Species Inventory (a comprehensive online resource on catfish) and Catfish Bones (an online digital atlas of catfish morphology), and is a participant in Neodat II (an online resource of Neotropic ichthyology collections).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Two of the early members of the Academy, Thomas Say and Isaac Lea, were malacologists (see also conchologists).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tucker Abbott, Samuel Stehman Haldeman, Henry A.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tryon, Jr. were other noted malacologists who worked at the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's malacology collection is the oldest such collection in the United States and is the 3rd largest in the world.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It currently contains over 10 million specimens, including types erected by more than 400 authors.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Curator Gary Rosenberg, an expert on Jamaican land snails, is a leader in digitised museum collections and research data.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research websites include the Malacology Georeferencing Project an online database of Western Atlantic Marine Mollusca (Malacolog) Archived September 24, 2015, at the Wayback Machine, and the OBIS Indo-Pacific Mollusc database.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Research associate and former curator Danielle Graf, an expert on Unionidae (freshwater mussels), maintains the MUSSEL Project web site.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The majority of ornithologists active in the United States during the first half of the 19th century, including Charles Lucien Bonaparte, George Ord, Titian Ramsay Peale, John James Audubon, John Cassin, Thomas Nuttall, and John Kirk Townsend, were active members of the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Later notable Academy ornithologists include James Bond, Frank Gill, Rodolphe Meyer de Schauensee, Pete Myers, Fred Sheldon, and Witmer Stone.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] With nearly 200,000 specimens representing over 9,000 species, the Ornithology collection is one of the largest and most taxonomically complete bird collections in the world.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Delaware Valley Ornithological Club (DVOC) has held regular meetings at the Academy since 1890.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Vertebrate paleontology in the United States originated in Philadelphia through the efforts of naturalists and scientists associated with the American Philosophical Society (APS) during the first decade of the 19th century and at The Academy of Natural Sciences thereafter.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] By the end of the 19th century, the holdings from the APS, including the Thomas Jefferson Fossil Collection, had been transferred to the Academy for safekeeping.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently, the collection contains more than 22,000 specimens, including many types.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Richard Harlan was an early member who introduced many American naturalists to the groundbreaking works of Georges Cuvier.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Joseph Leidy, who described *Hadrosaurus* and alerted the scientific world to the paleontological treasures of the American West, is considered the "father" of American vertebrate paleontology.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Edward Drinker Cope, who also worked extensively on other vertebrates, is best known for his rivalry with Othniel Charles Marsh during the infamous Bone Wars.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Daeschler is currently studying the evolution of Devonian tetrapods, but he will be retiring in September 2023.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] He is a co-discoverer of the transitional "fishapod" *Tiktaalik roseae* from the Canadian Arctic and the discoverer of two tetrapods, *Hynerpeton* and *Densignathus* from the Catskill Formation in Pennsylvania.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy houses several collections of smaller size yet historical and scientific importance.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The general invertebrate collection contains about 22,600 specimens, while the invertebrate paleontology collection contains about 105,000 lots.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Generally, 21,500 specimens are gaunt, 13,500 are affiliated skins, and 1,700 are wet-preserved specimens.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Myers Rotifer Collection is the most comprehensive collection of rotifers on microslides.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The herpetology collection contains about 40,000 specimens, including more than 500 type specimens.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The mammalogy collection contains about 36,000 specimens and 180 holotypes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Among the naturalists and scientists associated with these collections are Timothy Conrad, Edward Drinker Cope, Richard Harlan, John Edwards Holbrook, William W.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jefferis, Henry Charles Lea, Isaac Lea, Joseph Leidy, Samuel George Morton, and Thomas Say.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Formerly the Limnology Department, the Patrick Center for Environmental Research focuses on applied ecology.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Founded in 1947 by Ruth Patrick, formerly of the Diatom Herbarium, it was one of the earliest U.S. environmental consulting concerns.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its attachment to the Academy led it to become the first to employ interdisciplinary teams of scientists to study freshwater systems and the first to regard biodiversity as a central criterion of water quality.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its 1948 biological survey of the Conestoga River Basin in Pennsylvania, a milestone in environmental research, led to similar surveys and studies throughout much of the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Characteristically, these earlier projects were joint projects of the Limnology Department and private industry.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since the rise of the environmental movement in the 1960s and 1970s and the resulting increases in governmental regulation of water pollution, the environmental assessments pioneered at the Academy are increasingly conducted by private environmental consulting firms.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of the work employs most of the center's expertise and capabilities, such as recent studies on the ecological effects of small dams or the ecological benefits of riparian reforestation.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other studies may involve only one or a couple of the research programs.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] For example, a current project sampling sediment cores in tidal marshes throughout the Delaware Estuary.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] This undertaking, possibly the most comprehensive core sampling in any estuary, relies extensively on the center's expertise in biogeochemistry and phycology.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Once the sampling is completed, scientist will be able to investigate historical trends in marsh development, carbon, nitrogen and phosphorus cycling, water pollution, salinity variations, and climatic change by analysing the core's sediments, chemistry, and diatom assemblages.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Biogeochemistry Section of the Patrick Center is concerned with the influence of aquatic organisms on the sources, fate and transport of chemicals in aquatic systems.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies frequently deal with the carbon and nutrient cycling as well as those of trace elements (e.g., lead, copper, mercury, and zinc) and organic contaminants such as polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), and polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The section regularly provides water, sediment and tissue analyses for government, intergovernmental agencies, and private companies from around the country.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to the sediment core project mentioned above, it has recently studied the effects of small dams on sediment contaminants, photochemical transformation of marsh-derived dissolved organic matter, and sedimentation and eutrophication in salt marshes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Ecological Modeling Section employs sophisticated and rigorous mathematical modelling techniques to address a variety of questions in basic and applied research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Examples include watershed-scale modeling and risk assessment; nonlinear population models structured by age, body size, or space; particle transport in turbulent aquatic systems; and the ecology and control of exotic invasive plants in urban parks.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Fisheries Section of the Patrick Center conducts research into the ecology, conservation, and management of lotic and estuarine fishes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Studies may range from the analysis of fish tissues for contaminants, monitoring fish populations for environmental assessments, to investigating the life histories of individual species.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Benthic macroinvertebrates (primarily aquatic insects, crustaceans, and mollusks) are useful for biological monitoring programs.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Their varied life spans, ranging from weeks to years, are long enough to reveal intermittent and continuous pollutants, yet short enough respond to worsening or improving water quality.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Macroinvertebrate Section at the Patrick Center has extensive experience in bioassessment, biomonitoring, and inventorying of freshwater habitats throughout the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Because of their great diversity and specific ecological requirements, algae, particularly diatoms, make excellent indicators of water quality.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Moreover, diatoms are readily preserved in sediments, which make them useful organisms for studying paleolimnology (the long-term trends of streams and lakes).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Phycology Section of the Patrick Center provides algal analyses for governmental and other agencies interested in both assessing water quality and long-term environmental trends.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] One such undertaking is the analyses of diatom assemblages in lake sediments (sediment cores) throughout the eastern United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] This work, part of a large project managed by the EPA, will try to establish reference (pre-anthropogenic) conditions for lakes throughout the country.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to these research efforts, the Phycology Section of the Patrick Center has developed a set of online resources Archived September 6, 2019, at the Wayback Machine for using algae in environmental research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] These include an algal image database, autecology datasets for freshwater algae, algae research with the USGS National Water-Quality Assessment (NAWQA) program, and a diatom paleolimnology database.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] For most of its history, biological taxonomy and systematics were conducted using comparative morphology.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In recent decades, however, advances in molecular biology and computational technologies have opened new possibilities for studying the diversity and history of life through the use of cladistics and computational phylogenetics.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] These technologies also offer new opportunities for molecular ecology and conservation genetics.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy scientists have been early adapters of molecular biology techniques.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Allozymes, DNA-DNA hybridization, immunoelectrophoresis, restriction site analyses of mitochondrial DNA and serology were used extensively since the late 1960s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent molecular work mainly employs DNA sequencing, microsatellites, and AFLP (amplified fragment length polymorphism).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2004, the Laboratory for Molecular Systematics and Ecology (LMSE) was formed as a shared, multi-user facility to improve access to and provide training for the use of molecular data in systematic and ecological research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition to supporting staff, the lab offers research opportunities for students and post-doctoral fellowships.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy's work in Mongolia started with the realization of the unique research opportunities available at Lake Hovsgol (Hovsgol Nuur).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] This large lake and its watershed were remarkably pristine and relatively unknown, especially in comparison to its sister lake in Russia, Lake Baikal.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, a multidisciplinary team of scientists from the Academy, as well as from other American institutions, Mongolia, Russia, and Japan started a multi-year study of the lake's biodiversity, limnology, and watershed.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Although this research was scientifically rewarding, it was apparent that issues concerning environmental protection and sustainable economic development needed addressing.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Consequently, work at Hovsgol shifted to ecosystem studies and capacity building.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] One early undertaking was the enhancement of the operational and physical infrastructure at Hovsgol National Park.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Long-term ecological monitoring of several tributary watersheds began in 1997 and soon the site would be adopted into the International Long Term Ecological Research Network.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent work at Hovsgol is focusing on the consequences of and sustainable responses to climate change.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The region lies in a transitional zone between the semi-arid Eurasian Steppe (grasslands) to the south and the Eurasian Taiga (boreal forest) to the north.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] As such, it is an ideal mid-continental site at which to monitor the ecological effects of climate change.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, changes in livestock herding practices raise concerns about overgrazing and desertification.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In response, the team at Hovsgol created and distributed a *Herder Handbook* and continues to conduct research and work with nomadic herders to develop sustainable practices.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Mongolian Aquatic Insect Survey is a multi-year biodiversity survey, environmental monitoring and capacity building project managed by Jon Gelhaus of the Academy's Entomology Department.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] A total of 217 sites from the Selenge River Basin, the most populous and most extensive drainage in Mongolia, were surveyed from 2003 to 2006.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Most of these sites are in rivers or streams, but some are in freshwater and saltwater lakes, hot and cold springs, and marsh wetlands.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Additional sites from the remote drainage systems in western Mongolia will be sampled in 2008.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The survey has yielded numerous new species and hundreds of geographic records for known aquatic insects, provided an extensive dataset for ongoing environmental monitoring, and has helped develop research and technical infrastructures in Mongolia.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] This capacity building includes, in collaboration with the Institute of Meteorology and Hydrology, the building of the first research laboratory in Mongolia dedicated to the study of aquatic invertebrates.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It also includes training of Mongolian scientists and students.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Center for Environmental Policy informs and engages various constituents, promotes solutions, and builds public and professional awareness on important environmental topics.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Much of its activities focus on public programs and working groups.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center hosts or participates in a number of public programs that are free and open to the public.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Urban Sustainability Forums feature panels of local and national experts discussing environmental and sustainability topics as they relate to the Philadelphia region.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Town Square, which may feature a panel or an individual, addresses a variety of topics relating to the environment or public science.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center also hosts candidate forums, conferences and workshops.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The center acts as a logistical hub for a number of Working Groups organized around sustainability issues.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Currently active groups include one for condominium and building co-op owners, a network of faith-based environmental groups, and a forum of senior executives in the private sector.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Library and Archives were established at the Academy's founding meeting in 1812 for the purpose of supporting its natural science research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library provides online access, services, collections, imaging, and shared resources with other libraries.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The library houses nearly 200,000 volumes ranging from works published in the 16th century to current journals and books.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Its holdings also include illustrated works from as early as the 15th century, including Konrad Gessner's *Historia animalium*, Maria Sibylla Merian's *Insects of Surinam*, Edward Lear's *Psittacidae or Parrots*, and a double elephant folio of John James Audubon's *The Birds of America*.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal of the Academy of Natural Sciences* was the first peer-reviewed publication in the United States devoted to the natural sciences.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] By 1842, it had been superseded by the *Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences*.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Proceedings* have been published continuously since 1841.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Journal* was reborn in 1847 as a larger-format publication that could accommodate longer articles and monographs.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy publishes three other series.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The occasional series *Notulae Naturae* began in 1939 as a means to quickly publish short items, usually not longer than 16 pages on subject areas such as zoology, botany, ecology, geology and paleontology.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Monographs* series, which began in 1935, is composed principally of larger systematic reviews of selected taxonomic groups.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The *Special Publications* series, begun in 1922, includes works such as biography, taxonomy, historical reviews, and collections surveys.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO (VIsual REsource for Ornithology) is the most comprehensive collection of bird images in the world.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Started in 1979, the collection contains over 180,000 photographs representing over 7,300 species.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The collection contains work by some of the world's most talented photographers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] VIREO licenses bird images for a wide variety of commercial and non-profit uses.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy first opened its collections to the public in 1828.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The popularity of its exhibits soared in 1868 with the debut of the world's first mounted dinosaur skeleton, *Hadrosaurus*.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The size of the crowds flocking to this display prompted the Academy to relocate to its present-and roomier-location in 1876.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] As with most museums in the 19th century, there was little separation of the Academy's collections, which were vital to scientific work, and the public spaces.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Not only did this subject the collections to extra wear and tear, but visitors were typically confronted with a bewildering assemblage of specimens with little in the way of supplemental information.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Over time, however, museums such as the Academy started to showcase their more popular specimens while sequestering the bulk of the collections.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, they spent more effort interpreting their public displays.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Museums started to play a more active role in educating the public.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] One expression of this transformation was the rise of that icon of natural history museums, the diorama.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] These three-dimensional displays were the virtual reality of their time, providing generations of museum visitors with their only opportunity to experience distant places and exotic wildlife.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green created The Academy's first diorama, depicting rocky mountain goats.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Green's work was at first controversial amongst The Academy's staff, due to both the cost and accusations of sensationalism, but proved popular amongst the public.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1935, the Works Progress Administration began providing artists to help work on the dioramas, fueling the exhibits' continued expansion.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] By presenting the wilderness to the public, dioramas nurtured an appreciation of our natural heritage, which, coincided with the growth of the Conservation Movement in the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy currently has 37 dioramas, most of which were installed in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] They feature a variety of animals from Africa, Asia, and North America.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Some of these, such as the caribou, lion, and plains zebra are familiar and relatively common, but others, such as the desert bighorn, kiang, Kodiak bear, panda, and passenger pigeon, are threatened, endangered, or extinct.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 2018, under the management of Drexel University, The Academy renovated some of the older dioramas.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] These renovations were meant to increase the scientific accuracy of the displays and improve their aesthetics.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Another icon of natural history museums is the dinosaur skeleton.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The first of these, the *Hadrosaurus* mount created by noted natural history artist Benjamin Waterhouse Hawkins, made its debut at the Academy in 1868.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] *Hadrosaurus* mounts also found their way into other public venues, including Princeton University, the Royal Scottish Museum, the Smithsonian, and the 1876 American Centennial Exposition.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] A special exhibit on the history of *Hadrosaurus foulkii* ran from November 22, 2008 to April 19, 2009.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] A skeletal mount of a related dinosaur, *Corythosaurus*, served as the centerpiece of the Academy's "Hall of Earth History" during the middle of the 20th century.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1986, the Academy opened a new exhibit, "Discovering Dinosaurs".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] This was the first large-scale exhibit to incorporate the findings of the "dinosaur renaissance".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Instead of cold-blooded and lumbering reptiles, dinosaurs were conceived as active-and possibly warm-blooded-animals more akin to birds than reptiles.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, another type of dinosaur was the subject of an exhibition at the academy when it featured Jim Gary's Twentieth Century Dinosaurs and found that it was an enormous success with the public.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1979, the academy also opened "Outside-In", a hands-on children's nature museum.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In 1995, it pioneered the hands-on simulation of a dinosaur dig, with its "The Big Dig".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Other permanent exhibits include "Secrets of the Diorama", an insight into what goes into a diorama, and "Science at the Academy", which showcases current Academy research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The museum also has special, changing exhibits.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Recent changing exhibits include "Skin: Living Armor, Evolving Identity", "Illuminating Birds", "Extreme Deep: Mission to the Abyss", and "Crocs: Ancient Predators in a Modern World".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Four weekend festivals organized around scientific disciplines, are held during the year.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Paleopalooza, held in mid-February, features fossil collections and talks by leading paleontologists.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Earth Day Festival, held in mid-April, features scientists from the Academy's Patrick Center for Environmental Research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Bug Fest, held in mid August, features entomologists, insect collections and live insects.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Philadelphia Shell Show, held in mid-October, features an international shell market and competitive shell displays.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Academy began offering lectures to the public as early as the 1820s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Current offerings include natural history author talks, lectures by scientists, workshops and classes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, the Center for Environmental Policy produces public programs on environmental issues.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its Nature Club in the 1930s, the Academy has offered programming just for children.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Several programs appropriate for different age groups are currently offered.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Safari Overnight sleepovers (camp-ins) are held on selected weekends during Fall, Winter, and Spring.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Boy Scouts and Girl Scouts can participate in day workshops and sleepovers to fulfill badge and pin requirements.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Tiny Tot Explorers is a program for toddlers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] A new series of Family Workshops designed for both adults and children was launched in early 2010.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Wild Weekends", held on selected weekends throughout the year, offer a variety of children's programs, including hands-on exploration of museum specimens, crafts and live animal shows with mammals, birds and reptiles.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Live animal shows are also presented at regular times on other days and featured prominently in the educational programs.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Field trips to the Academy are available throughout the year for schools, summer camps and other groups.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Optional directed programs include Discovery Lessons for younger age groups (pre-K and higher) and Science Explorers for older children (grades 7 through 9).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] "Academy on the Go" is an educational outreach program that visits schools, camps, and community centers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] WINS (Women in Natural Sciences) is an innovative and successful science enrichment program conducted by The Academy of Natural Sciences in collaboration with the School District of Philadelphia.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Since its founding in 1982, WINS has been providing female public school students with hands-on science classes, scientific literacy and skill-building activities, and opportunities for personal growth in a uniquely nurturing setting.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Academy Explorers Camp is a day camp program offered during Spring Break and the Summer.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The George Washington Carver Science Fair is held in February or March.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Science fair participants are eligible for the George Washington Carver Scholars summer program, which is also held at the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Educator workshops are held throughout the year.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The most recent series covered the integration of science and literacy skills.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Self-guided workbooks tailored for younger children are available for some of the museum exhibits.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Hayden Memorial Geological Award is given to prominent scientists working in geology or paleontology.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1888 in memory of Ferdinand V.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Hayden, a distinguished American geologist and pioneering surveyor of the American West who had extensive ties to the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Established in 1980, the Gold Medal for Distinction in Natural History Art is awarded to people whose artistic endeavors and life's work have contributed to our understanding and appreciation of living things.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Richard Hopper Day Memorial Medal, established in 1960 by his granddaughter, Margaret Day Dilks, is awarded in recognition of outstanding contributions in interpreting the natural sciences to the public.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Joseph Leidy Award honors research in the natural sciences.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] It was established in 1923 as a tribute to the many contributions and long association of Joseph Leidy with the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Böhlke Memorial Endowment Fund honors the memory of James E.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Böhlke who were prominent ichthyologists at the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] This fund provides support for graduate students and recent postdoctoral researchers to work with the Ichthyology Collection and the Academy's Library.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Gallagher Fellowship provides a unique opportunity for original, multi-year, postdoctoral or sabbatical research on the systematics of microscopic invertebrates, especially Rotifera.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The research focus must be on systematics and may employ ecological, behavioral, physiological, molecular or developmental tools.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] Jessup and McHenry Awards are competitively awarded to students wishing to conduct studies at the postgraduate, doctoral and postdoctoral levels under the supervision or sponsorship of a member of the curatorial staff of the Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Jessup Award is given for any specialty in which our curators have expertise.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The McHenry Fund is restricted to botanists.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] The Eckelberry Endowment helps support the efforts of wildlife painters, sculptors, printmakers, and other artists to better acquaint themselves with the natural world through both museum and field research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/academy-of-natural-sciences] In addition, artistic and scientific mentors counsel and assist these artists as their careers develop.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Born in Switzerland to a Protestant minister, Gatschet studied at universities in Switzerland and Germany before immigrating to the United States in 1868, where he worked as a language teacher.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In 1872, the German botanist Oscar Loew asked him to analyze sixteen American Indian vocabularies recorded during the Wheeler Survey.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His analysis was presented to the United States Congress and culminated in a German-language book which earned him the attention of Major John Wesley Powell, who hired Gatschet as an ethnologist for the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet was later a founding member of the Bureau of American Ethnology and spent the majority of his life traveling the United States and completing surveys of the nation's languages en masse.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet's work remains highly regarded; his ethnological and linguistic publications on Indigenous peoples and their languages are considered to have pioneered the field.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His reorganization of the language families of Indigenous languages earned him significant appreciation during his lifetime.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His work on the Klamath people earned him particular praise, including from the people themselves several decades after his death.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The American linguist Ives Goddard described Gatschet's work as part of the driving force behind a period of transition away from missionary-based linguistic study and towards a view based on scientific interest.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Albert Louis Samuel Gatschet was born on October 3, 1832, in Saint Beatenberg, Switzerland, the second child and only son of Mary (née Ziegler) and Karl Albert Gatschet, a Protestant minister.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Mary died when Albert was about ten years old, and he was thereafter raised in part by his older sister, Louise.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Following his mother's death, Albert's loss was made more difficult by his father's severe disposition, though he remained extremely affectionate towards his sister throughout his life.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In his youth, Gatschet's education was primarily religious, and he considered becoming a reverend like his father.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He attended the *gymnasia* in Neuchâtel and Bern.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet attended the University of Bern from 1852 to 1858, studying languages, history, art, and theology; his favorite subjects there were Ancient Greek and theological doctrinal criticism.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The same year he left the University of Bern, he began studying languages at the University of Berlin.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Although he had published a handful of articles before, Gatschet published his first major work in 1867, *Ortsetymologische Forschungen aus der Schweiz* ('Toponymic Etymological Research in Switzerland') which dealt with the etymological origins of place names around his native Switzerland.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The book met with critical success and remained a standard reference work until his death.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet spent several months following its publication working at various museums in Paris and London, including the British Museum, before immigrating to the United States the following January where he settled in New York City.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In New York, Gatschet continued to publish linguistics articles but worked primarily as a language teacher, being fluent in both French and German, though he reportedly had difficulty with English.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In 1872, he was given the recorded vocabularies of sixteen American Indian languages to analyze by the German botanist Oscar Loew, who had been attached to the Wheeler Survey tasked with exploring the Southwestern United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet's analyses of the vocabularies were reported in the 1875 and 1876 volumes of the Wheeler reports, culminating in another publication entitled *Zwölf Sprachen aus dem Südwesten Nordamerikas*.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Although *Zwölf Sprachen* was published in Weimar, the publication earned Gatschet the attention of John Wesley Powell, a major in the United States Army, then serving as Director of the Geographical and Geological Survey of the Rocky Mountain Region.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In March 1877, Gatschet accepted an offer from Powell to become an ethnologist under him in order to classify and document the languages of the region, prompting Gatschet to relocate to Washington, D.C., permanently.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Upon his arrival, he began working with the Smithsonian Institution to classify its existing documentation of American Indian languages, including a five-year effort to classify and describe the Yuman languages of the Southwest.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The same year, the government commissioned him to formulate a comprehensive account of the Pacific Northwest beginning with an expedition, to the Otaki village of the Maidu in the Sacramento Valley and later visiting the Modoc and Kalapuya peoples, among others.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] There, he also began his work on the Klamath people in and around modern-day border of Oregon and California.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In 1879, Gatschet became a founding member of the Bureau of American Ethnology, with Powell as its new director.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet was among several linguists who were deployed to different parts of the country to reassess classifications.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In December 1881, Gatschet traveled to South Carolina where he discovered the relationship between the local Catawba language and the Siouan languages of the Great Plains.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Between 1881 and 1882, Gatschet traveled to Louisiana and studied the area's remnant languages in an attempt to classify them; at the time of his death, his work was the only extant phylogenetic analysis ever undertaken for several of the languages he studied.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In January 1885, Gatschet traveled to the city of Lake Charles to begin work on the Atakapa language.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] There, he discovered the last village of the tribe – Túl Núŋ – experiencing a mass exodus as tribesmen who could speak the language began migrating to Texas and Oklahoma.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet worked with "the two most knowledgeable speakers of the language" – cousins Kišyuc ('Will-o'-the-Wisp') and Tottokš ('Round [Eyes]') – in the village.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He later published a plea encouraging others to study the language, but it was unsuccessful during his lifetime.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The year after Gatschet's death, John R.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Swanton took up the plea, publishing a good portion of Gatschet's notes and finishing his dictionary by 1932.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] While Swanton attempted to conduct his own research, he found the tribe somewhat reluctant to speak to outsiders and a significant portion of his work has been lost entirely.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Although a handful of vocabularies existed prior, Gatschet's work on Atakapa's grammar is the only extant source.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Later that year, Gatschet's work took him to Oklahoma, where he undertook the first major survey of the Yuchi language.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He traveled back to Louisiana in 1885 and 1886 to study Tunica, Chitimacha, Biloxi, and two dialects of Choctaw.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Further studies in 1886 took him across the Rio Grande into Mexico to study the last six speakers of the Carrizo language.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His work in Mexico took him as far south as Saltillo to the Nahuatl-speaking Tlaxcalteca.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet also made a number of contributions to the study of other languages indigenous to the Gulf coast of modern-day Texas.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His two-word recording of the Haname language from a Tonkawa elder in 1884 (*Himia'na tsa'yi!* 'Give me water!') is the only documentation of the language.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In November 1888, he traveled to Lynn, Massachusetts, to help complete an account of the Karankawa language, originally spoken in Texas.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He was able to review early works with his informant Alice Oliver while also eliciting new vocabulary.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Oliver was then a sixty-year-old white woman from Matagorda who had learned the language in her childhood.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] An attempt to link the language other local Texan languages was about to be underway, but Oliver died the following February.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The work Gatschet was able to complete was published in 1891, which covered both the language and some ethnographic notes.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The work followed the publication of the *Creek Migration Legend* published in two volumes in 1884 and 1888, which served as an outline of much of his work on the Gulf coast.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The contemporary American ethnologist James Mooney described Gatschet's efforts on the Gulf coast and Mexico as being immeasurably bolstered by Gatschet's impressive command of both Spanish and French.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] However, Gatschet's studies were not entirely premised on travel and strict fieldwork; he often consulted local documentation – typically compiled by earlier missionaries – and other miscellany when he traveled, often by using his own vacation time.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In Washington, D.C., when American Indian delegations arrived to attend sessions of Congress, Gatschet was known to interview their members for several nights in a row.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] At the time of his death, a significant portion was still unpublished.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In 1890, Gatschet published *The Klamath Indians of Southwestern Oregon*, a more-than-1,500-page monograph published in two parts.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The second volume comprises both a Klamath–English dictionary and an English–Klamath one.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The work captures the language as it was spoken before it experienced significant contamination from the growing dominance of Chinook Jargon; Gatschet was discerning in distinguishing the speech of those who were already beginning to have their language affected by language contact.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The book was extremely well-received among its readership.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Decades after his death, *The National Cyclopædia of American Biography* described the publication as "one of the most exhaustive studies of an American native language ever undertaken and may fairly be said to mark an epoch in the science of linguistics".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Many Klamath expressed approval at his work as well, with one writing fifty years after his death that "his work with our Indians [...] can never be surpassed or even equaled".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In September 1892, Gatschet married Louise Horner, a widow from Philadelphia about twenty-four years his junior.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The same year, the University of Bern granted him an honorary doctorate.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet became a naturalized citizen of the United States on September 28, 1896.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Later in life, Gatschet became overly involved in his work to the point of neglecting his own health.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Before he left, he gave the Bureau a massive manuscript "probably equal in extent" to his Klamath publication, containing about ten thousand words of the Peoria language.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet's health began deteriorating rapidly following his retirement and he was constantly attended to by his wife.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His later life was marked with what his doctors referred to as fainting spells.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In July 1906, he collapsed in the street and had to be revived at Freedman's Hospital.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet died in Washington, D.C., on March 16, 1907, of Bright's disease and overwork at the age of 74.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Although later in life he had become unconcerned with spiritual matters altogether, an Episcopalian funeral service was held at his house on 15th Street three days after his death.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He was buried at Mount Peace Cemetery in Philadelphia the following day.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet is considered to be a pioneer in the study of American Indian peoples and their languages.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In 1902, *The Washington Post* described him as "among the greatest of American ethnologists, having done more toward ordering and classifying the disordered mass of American linguistics than any living authority on American philology".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Despite this, most of Gatschet's field notes remain unanalyzed as of 2020.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Although the majority of Gatschet's work was done in the United States, his work was better known and more highly regarded among European academics during his lifetime.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The American-French historian Henry Vignaud wrote that "he did much for his adopted homeland, where it can be said that he created the science of languages considered in their relationship to race".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Retrospectives have often compared Gatschet to his Swiss-American compatriots Albert Gallatin and Louis Agassiz, who also made substantial contributions to their scientific fields.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] The American linguist Ives Goddard described the efforts of Gatschet and James Owen Dorsey as "two men of unusual linguistic ability and equipment" who ushered in a period of linguistic interest motivated "by scientific interest rather than missionary zeal".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet's work examined over a hundred American Indian languages, many of which were critically endangered at the time of his documentation.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He wrote the first major works on Muskogee and Hitchiti, and began the only Atakapa-language dictionary.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] By 1902, he had published over a hundred works on Indigenous languages.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet's influence on the study of the Siouan languages is profound.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His work identified the Siouan-speaking peoples' *Urheimat* as having been closer to the East Coast of the United States than the Great Plains, as was previously assumed.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Linguists now believe Proto-Siouan was spoken in and around the Ohio River Valley.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] His work with the Biloxi people and their language on the Gulf Coast made him the first to identify the language as Siouan.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He was also a beneficiary member of the Bookbinders Guild of Bern.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In 1884, he was elected a member of the American Philosophical Society, followed by election to the American Antiquarian Society in 1902.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Although highly regarded for his work, Gatschet had a reputation for being solitary, emotionally distant, and unresponsive, which led to some tension between him and his colleagues.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In a letter to Wilberforce Eames, James Pilling – Powell's chief clerk – described Gatschet as "certainly more nearly devoid of all idea of courtesy and social decorum than any man I have ever met".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Pilling also berated Gatschet for continuing to browse his papers unsupervised and without permission.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Hewitt, another member of Powell's team, refused to speak to Gatschet at all.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] However, Gatschet's usefulness during the survey prompted Powell to protect him from the enmity of other members of the entourage.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] Gatschet's friend and colleague James Mooney wrote that "his chief characteristics were thoroughness and absolute honesty", but admitted that "it was practically impossible for him to collaborate" with others in his work.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] *The National Cyclopædia of American Biography* similarly described him as "a brilliant and painstaking scholar [...] of an unusually retiring nature and, by preference, most of his important work was accomplished alone".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] He was also known as morally upright, loyal, and unwilling to tolerate pseudoscience.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/albert-samuel-gatschet] In response to one such claim, he remarked: "To guess is not science".
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was born in Philadelphia, the son of Richard Bache, Jr., and Sophia Burrell Dallas Bache.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He came from a family prominent in American politics.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He was the nephew of Vice-President George M.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Dallas, the grandson of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Dallas, and the great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] After graduating from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1825, as first in his class, he was an assistant professor of engineering there for some time.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] As a second lieutenant in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, he was engaged in the construction of Fort Adams in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache resigned from the Army on June 1, 1829.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was a professor of natural philosophy and chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania from 1828 to 1841 and again from 1842 to 1843.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He spent 1836–1838 in Europe on behalf of the trustees of what became Girard College; he was named president of the college after his return.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Abroad, he examined European education systems, and on his return he published a valuable report.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] From 1839 to 1842, he served as the first president of Central High School of Philadelphia, one of the oldest public high schools in the United States.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1843, on the death of Professor Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler, Bache was appointed superintendent of the United States Coast Survey.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Whereas Hassler had faced continual doubts from Congress, Bache succeeded in convincing legislators of the value of geodesy in addition to geomagnetic and meteorological research.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] With many contacts, friends, and family among the nation's political and military leaders, Bache won liberal appropriations to build up his agency and greatly expand its work.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] By the mid 1850s it had become the federal government's leading scientific bureau.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1849, it began study of the Pacific Coast, which the US had newly acquired via the US-Mexico War and Oregon Treaty.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Assisted by Isaac Stevens, his number two in Washington, DC, Bache reorganized the Coast Survey so that it could complete initial mapping of the entire US coast.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] By the 1840s, a clique of leading US scientists began to coalesce around Bache with the goal of professionalizing their fields.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] They formalized with establishment of the Association of American Geologists and Naturalists in 1843 (renamed the American Association for the Advancement of Science five years later) and the Smithsonian Institution in 1846.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Informally, Bache and his circle called themselves the Scientific Lazzaroni.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Together, the groups created and enforced standards of intellectual merit with the goal of elevating the nation and its reputation.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] This meant discrediting charlatans but, at times, also denying research funding or academic appointments to others.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Perhaps most important, the groups advised and even mentored politicians and army engineers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache would lead the AAAS until 1851 and serve on the Smithsonian's board of regents throughout his term as Coast Survey superintendent.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1863, amid the demands of the Civil War, Bache was a central figure in the establishment of the National Academy of Sciences, created by an act of Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He was elected its first president and served in that role until his death in 1867.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] As the sectional crisis worsened through the late 1850s, Coast Survey budgets became ensnared by polarization and conflicts in Congress.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Then, the start of war in 1861 brought a stop to work along the South's Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache withdrew Survey ships from the region so they would not fall into secessionists' hands.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] At the same time, some staff resigned to join the Confederacy.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] A number of trusted friends and Democratic allies, including senators Jefferson Davis and Stephen Mallory, would lead the rebellion — acts that Bache took as both political and personal treachery.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Yet the Civil War enhanced the Coast Survey's stature in Washington, D.C.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] By this time, the agency had amassed charts of southern harbors, rivers, and coastal terrain.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] The research gave a critical advantage to the Union navy and army.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Meanwhile, Bache continued to lead scientists to greater influence in government, helping to establish the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He also played a central role in the founding of the National Academy of Sciences in 1863 and served as its first president.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] Official duties and private worries contributed to Bache's declining health.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] By 1864 he had suffered a stroke, which left him handicapped and unable to work without his wife's assistance.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] At the time of his death, he had served as head of the Coast Survey for 24 years.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] After the Civil War, Bache was elected a 3rd Class Companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States (MOLLUS) in consideration of his contributions to the war effort.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He married Nancy Clark Fowler on September 30, 1838, in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] She was born in Newport and died on January 13, 1870, in Philadelphia.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] She assisted in the publication of much of his work.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] They adopted one son, Henry Wood Bache (1839–1878).
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He died at Newport, Rhode Island on February 17, 1867, from cerebral softening.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/alexander-dallas-bache] He was buried in the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., under a monument designed by architect Henry Hobson Richardson.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] Brinton was born in Thornbury Township, Chester County, Pennsylvania.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] After graduating from Yale University in 1858, Brinton studied at Jefferson Medical College for two years and spent the next year traveling in Europe.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] He continued his studies at Paris and Heidelberg.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] From 1862 to 1865, during the American Civil War, he was a surgeon in the Union army, acting during 1864–1865 as surgeon-in-charge of the U.S.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] Army general hospital at Quincy, Illinois.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] Brinton was sun-stroked at Missionary Ridge (Third Battle of Chattanooga) and was never again able to travel in very hot weathers.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] This handicap affected his career as an ethnologist.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] At his presidential address to the American Association for the Advancement of Science in August 1895, Brinton advocated theories of scientific racism that were pervasive at that time.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] Brinton was an anarchist during his last several years of life.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] In April 1896, he addressed the Ethical Fellowship of Philadelphia with a lecture on "What the Anarchists Want," to a friendly audience.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] In October 1897, Brinton had dinner with Peter Kropotkin after the famous anarchist's only speaking engagement at Philadelphia.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] Kropotkin had refused invitations from all of the city's elites.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] On the occasion of his memorial meeting on October 6, 1900, the keynote speaker Albert H.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] From 1868 to 1899, Brinton wrote many books, and a large number of pamphlets, brochures, addresses and magazine articles.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] In addition, he edited and published a Library of American Aboriginal Literature (8 vols.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] 1882–1890), a valuable contribution to the science of anthropology in America.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] Of the eight volumes; six were edited by Brinton himself, one by Horatio Hale and one by Albert Samuel Gatschet.
[src:daniel-garrison-brinton/daniel-garrison-brinton] His 1885 work is notable for its role in the Walam Olum controversy.
